<DOC><DOCNO> AP890517-0174 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 2031EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-CalifCorruption     05-17 0214</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Calif Corruption,0219</SECOND><HEAD>State Senator Charged with Corruption After Undercover Probe</HEAD><DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal grand jury indicted a statesenator and his former aide Wednesday on bribery and extortioncharges.   Joseph Montoya, chairman of the Senate Business and ProfessionsCommittee, was indicted as a result of a three-year FBI undercoverinvestigation. The investigation became public in August whenfederal agents searched the Capitol offices of Montoya and threeother legislators.   U.S. Attorney David Levi said Montoya, a Democrat, and Amiel A.Jaramillo were named in a 12-count indictment under twoanti-corruption laws, the Racketeer Influenced, CorruptOrganizations Act and the Hobbs Act.   The indictment says Montoya and Jaramillo used the office ofstate senator ``to unlawfully obtain campaign contributions andother payments, including speaking fees.''   In the FBI probe, federal agents posed as businessmen and set upphony companies that dispensed at least $90,000 to lawmakers andpolitical consultants in return for favors, according to publicdocuments and private business records.   Montoya and Jaramillo were not available to comment, an aidetold a reporter at Montoya's office.   Montoya faces maximum penalties of 160 years in prison and $1million in fines, plus forfeiture of any illegally acquiredproperty if convicted. Jaramillo faces 80 years in prison and$250,000 in fines.</TEXT></DOC>